      <hedline>
        <hl1>Death, Taxes and Simple Fairness</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jacqueline Rudman letter on June 11 editorial holds estate tax is unfair and should be repealed</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Gift to the Wealthiest'' (editorial, June 11):</p>
        <p>I take exception to your thesis that a repeal of the estate tax is a ''gift.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Gift to the Wealthiest'' (editorial, June 11):</p>
        <p>I take exception to your thesis that a repeal of the estate tax is a ''gift.''</p>
        <p>When did it become a disgrace in the United States to work hard, be successful, save regularly and invest wisely?</p>
        <p>When did it become unacceptable to want to pass on to your children and grandchildren something more tangible than good advice? When did keeping the fruits of your labor become a ''gift''?</p>
        <p>We all pay taxes on earned income. Then we pay taxes on our investments. Why, then, should we pay a third tax because we prudently did not squander all our assets in our lifetime?</p>
        <p>The reason so many Americans want this unfair, confiscatory law repealed is that Americans are incredibly fair-minded. They recognize injustice and want it stopped, even if they will not benefit personally.</p>
        <p>JACQUELINE  RUDMAN  Baroda, Mich., June 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
